Phase 1: On Your ONLINE Machine (The "Download" Step)
You need to gather three sets of files on your USB drive.

1. Gather System Packages (.deb files)
We need the installers for git, pip, venv, and the C++ build-essential tools. apt has a way to download packages without installing them.

Plug in your USB drive.

Open a terminal on your online Ubuntu machine (or a "live" Ubuntu USB).

Create a folder for all the system packages:

Bash

# (Assuming your USB is mounted at /media/user/MY_USB)
mkdir -p /media/user/MY_USB/system_packages
Important: Clear your apt cache to ensure you download fresh copies.

Bash

sudo apt clean
Tell apt to download only the packages and all their dependencies:

Bash

sudo apt install --download-only -y git python3-pip python3-venv build-essential
Now, copy all the downloaded .deb files from your system's apt cache into your USB folder.

Bash

# This copies all the .deb files you just downloaded
cp /var/cache/apt/archives/*.deb /media/user/MY_USB/system_packages/
2. Gather Python Libraries (Wheels)
Next, we need the Python libraries. pip also has a "download" command.

Create a folder on your USB for the Python files:

Bash

mkdir -p /media/user/MY_USB/python_wheels
Use pip download to get the libraries and all their dependencies.

Bash

pip download -d /media/user/MY_USB/python_wheels flask GitPython llama-cpp-python
This will fill your python_wheels folder with all the .whl and .tar.gz files needed.

3. Download the AI Model (.gguf file)
This is just a single file download. Save it directly to your USB.

Go to this URL in your browser: https://huggingface.co/TheBloke/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2-GGUF/resolve/main/mistral-7b-instruct-v0.2.Q4_K_M.gguf

Your browser will download the model.gguf file (it's ~4.37 GB).

Save or move this file to the root of your USB drive.

Phase 2: On Your OFFLINE Machine (The "Install" Step)
You are now back at your offline Ubuntu computer. Plug in the USB drive.

1. Install System Packages
Open a terminal and navigate to the system_packages folder on your USB:

Bash

# (Your USB might be at a different path)
cd /media/user/MY_USB/system_packages
Install all the .deb files at once. Using apt this way is smart—it will figure out the correct dependency order from the files in the folder.

Bash

# This tells apt to install all .deb files in the current directory
sudo apt install ./*.deb
This will install git, pip, venv, and all the C++ build tools.

2. Install Python Libraries
First, create your project folder and virtual environment, just as we planned:

Bash

mkdir ~/ai_assistant
cd ~/ai_assistant
python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate
Now, tell pip to install the libraries. We must use two special flags:

--no-index: This is critical. It tells pip "DO NOT connect to the internet."

--find-links: This tells pip "Look in this local folder for the files you need."

Run this command (replace the USB path with your actual path):

Bash

pip install --no-index --find-links=/media/user/MY_USB/python_wheels flask GitPython llama-cpp-python
pip will now install all the libraries and their dependencies from your USB. The llama-cpp-python installation will use the C++ build tools you installed in the previous step to compile itself.

3. Copy the AI Model
Finally, copy the model file into your new project folder:

Bash

cp /media/user/MY_USB/model.gguf ~/ai_assistant/
✅ Setup Complete (Offline)
You have now successfully installed everything on a completely offline machine.

Your ai_assistant folder is ready and contains:

ai_assistant/
├── venv/          (Your Python virtual environment with all libraries)
└── model.gguf     (The AI model file)
